# Perform k-means clustering and chose a value of k.

we will use the 3 different method to check how many K should we use in customer data.

library(factoextra)
 fviz_nbclust(customers_scaled, 
             kmeans, 
             method = "wss", 
             nstart = 25)

fviz_nbclust(customers_scaled, 
             kmeans, 
             method = "silhouette", 
             nstart = 25)

fviz_nbclust(customers_scaled, 
             kmeans, 
             method = "gap_stat", 
             nstart = 25, 
             k.max = 10)

The 3 different method confirm that the K should be 6.

Visualise the clustering k = 6.

library(broom)

 max_k <- 6 

k_clusters <- tibble(k = 1:max_k) %>%
  mutate(
    kclust = map(k, ~ kmeans(customers_scaled, .x, nstart = 25)), 
    tidied = map(kclust, tidy),
    glanced = map(kclust, glance),
    augmented = map(kclust, augment, customers)
  )

k_clusters
## # A tibble: 6  5
##       k kclust   tidied           glanced          augmented         
##   <int> <list>   <list>           <list>           <list>            
## 1     1 <kmeans> <tibble [1  6]> <tibble [1  4]> <tibble [200  4]>
## 2     2 <kmeans> <tibble [2  6]> <tibble [1  4]> <tibble [200  4]>
## 3     3 <kmeans> <tibble [3  6]> <tibble [1  4]> <tibble [200  4]>
## 4     4 <kmeans> <tibble [4  6]> <tibble [1  4]> <tibble [200  4]>
## 5     5 <kmeans> <tibble [5  6]> <tibble [1  4]> <tibble [200  4]>
## 6     6 <kmeans> <tibble [6  6]> <tibble [1  4]> <tibble [200  4]>
k_clusters %>% 
  unnest(cols = c(augmented)) %>%
  ggplot() +
  aes(y = spending_score_1_100,
      x = annual_income_k,
      color = .cluster) +
  geom_point(aes(color = .cluster))

# Do you think the clustering seems a good fit for this data?
